<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1138,1489]" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">
This is a large, endemic Chinese species with a relatively wide distribution range, including 
<collectingRegion box="[1217,1344,1138,1164]" country="China" name="Chongqing" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Chongqing</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1358,1432,1138,1164]" country="China" name="Gansu" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Gansu</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[151,250,1174,1200]" country="China" name="Guizhou" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Guizhou</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[261,337,1174,1200]" country="China" name="Henan" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Henan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[348,419,1174,1200]" country="China" name="Hubei" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Hubei</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[430,507,1174,1200]" country="China" name="Hunan" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Hunan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[519,603,1174,1200]" country="China" name="Jiangxi" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Jiangxi</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[613,706,1174,1200]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[763,852,1174,1200]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
. The body size and color pattern are quite consistent throughout all populations. Cerci are special with the apex extended and the basal prominence long, cylindrical, foot-like (
<figureCitation box="[263,329,1246,1273]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1420,1444]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,195,1385]" captionTargetId="figure-34@14.[151,1436,181,1396]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Caudal appendages of males (dorsal view). a) australis; b) irma, paratype; c) distans, from Yaan, Sichuan; d) distans from Dashahe, Guizhou; e) heros; f) omeiensis, paratype; g) kurahashii; h) major; i) haui; j) “palaceus”; k) micans, bd: basal disk; l) “chengi”; m) riccii; n) “maai”; o) “tuska,” from Damingshan, Guangxi; p) “tuska,” from Jinxiu, Guangxi. (Scale bar = 0.5 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407489/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
c–d). The end of the genital ligula has terminal lateral lobes largely divergent and up-curved at the tips (
<figureCitation box="[207,290,1282,1309]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[214,1369,199,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-34@18.[205,1381,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Genital ligula of males (lateral view) (a–m) and ventral view (n–ab). a) australis; b) distans; c) heros; d) omeiensis, paratype; e) major; f) irma, paratype; g) “palaceus”; h) haui; i) “Chengi”; j) maai; k) riccii; l) tuska; m) micans; n) australis, Hr: horn; o) distans, Tlb: terminal lateral lobe; p) heros; q) omeiensis, paratype; r) major; s) irma, paratype; t) kurahashii; u) “palaceus”; v) haui; w) micans, from Jinping, Yunnan; x) “Chengi”; y) maai; z) riccii, Blb: basal lateral lobe; aa) tuska, Mlb: middle lateral lobe; ab) micans, from Fengyangshan, Zhejiang. (Scale bar = 0.2 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407495/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Fig. 5o</figureCitation>
). The basal teeth on paraprocts varied slightly among populations (
<figureCitation box="[1044,1112,1282,1309]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1443,1467]" captionTargetBox="[175,1424,244,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-56@15.[151,1437,237,1419]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 4. Caudal appendages of males (lateral view). a) australis; b) irma, paratype; c) distans, from Yaan, Sichuan; d) distans from Qingchengshan, Chengdu, Sichuan; e) heros; f) omeiensis, paratype; g) kurahashii; h) major; i) haui; j) “palaceus”; k) micans; l) “Chengi,” paratype; m) riccii; n) maai; o) tuska, from Damingshan, Guangxi; p) tuska, from Jinxiu, Guangxi. (Scale bar = 0.5 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407493/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
c–d). 
<bibRefCitation author="Needham, J. G." box="[1175,1364,1282,1308]" pageId="13" pageNumber="258" pagination="227 - 231" refId="ref14437" refString="Needham, J. G. (1930) A manual of the dragonflies of China. Peiping: The Fan Memorial Institute of Biology, 227 - 231." type="book chapter" year="1930">Needham (1930)</bibRefCitation>
stated that his specimens came from both 
<collectingRegion box="[552,648,1318,1344]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[704,798,1318,1344]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
. We checked through his original descriptions and could not find any localities belonging to 
<collectingRegion box="[557,656,1354,1380]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
, but the species is present in 
<collectingRegion box="[991,1081,1354,1380]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
with Yu Chi Valley as the 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,1354,1380]" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">type</typeStatus>
locality. 
<bibRefCitation author="Wilson, K. D. P. &amp; Reels, G. T." box="[248,511,1390,1416]" pageId="13" pageNumber="258" pagination="237 - 279" refId="ref15245" refString="Wilson, K. D. P. &amp; Reels, G. T. (2003) Odonata of Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, China, Part 1: Zygoptera. Odonatologica, 32, 237 - 279." type="journal article" year="2003">Wilson &amp; Reels (2003)</bibRefCitation>
reported several specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[896,996,1390,1416]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
. However, the figures and descriptions were not consistent with our specimens nor were they like those from 
<bibRefCitation author="Needham, J. G." box="[952,1144,1426,1452]" pageId="13" pageNumber="258" pagination="227 - 231" refId="ref14437" refString="Needham, J. G. (1930) A manual of the dragonflies of China. Peiping: The Fan Memorial Institute of Biology, 227 - 231." type="book chapter" year="1930">Needham (1930)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chao, H. - F." box="[1157,1301,1426,1453]" pageId="13" pageNumber="258" pagination="187 - 196" refId="ref13620" refString="Chao, H. - F. (1965) A study of the Chinese dragonflies of the genus Megalestes Selys, with description of a new species (Odonata: Synlestidae). Acta Zootaxonomica Sinica, 2, 187 - 196." type="journal article" year="1965">Chao (1965)</bibRefCitation>
, or 
<bibRefCitation author="Asahina, S." pageId="13" pageNumber="258" pagination="192 - 201" refId="ref13440" refString="Asahina, S. (1969) Notes on Chinese Odonata II, the Odonata of Metasequoia expedition. Kontyu, 37, 192 - 201." type="journal article" year="1969">Asahina (1969)</bibRefCitation>
. Therefore, we do not believe that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Needham" authorityYear="1930" box="[618,734,1462,1488]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="13" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distans">
<emphasis box="[618,734,1462,1488]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">M. distans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in 
<collectingRegion box="[850,950,1462,1488]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
